Here's the full migration analysis:

## Breaking Changes & Pitfalls

| Issue | .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `ThreadAbortException` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Works but fragile | Still works, but **not recommended** |
| Race condition | Multiple `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` → items silently lost | Same bug carries over |
| No graceful shutdown | Relies on `Abort` as fallback | Must use `CancellationToken` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

Replace the entire class with `Channel<T>`, which is the modern producer/consumer primitive:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _processingTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        // TryWrite always succeeds on unbounded channels
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();                // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline
        if (_processingTask is not null)
            await _processingTask;
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## Key Differences

1. **`Channel<T>` replaces `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock`** — thread-safe, no race conditions, no lost items.
2. **`CancellationToken` replaces `Abort`/`Interrupt`** — cooperative cancellation is the only supported pattern in .NET 8.
3. **`Task.Run` replaces `new Thread`** — uses the thread pool; avoids managing thread lifecycle manually.
4. **`Writer.Complete()` signals graceful drain** — the loop finishes remaining items before exiting. The `CancelAfter` acts as the hard-stop fallback.

## If You Need a Synchronous API

If callers can't use `async`, wrap `StopAsync`:

```csharp
public void Stop()
{
    StopAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5))
        .AsTask()
        .GetAwaiter()
        .GetResult();
}
```

## If `Handle` Is Async

Change the signature to `async Task HandleAsync(string item)` and simply `await` it inside `RunLoopAsync`. Channels compose naturally with async code — no extra plumbing needed.
